Question: Making assumptions about type parameters?: :I want to subclass Iterator into what I'll call FooIterator. My code looks something like this:public class FooIterator<E> implements Iterator<E> {  public FooIterator(Collection<Bar> bars) {    innerIterator = bars.iterator();  }  @Override  public boolean hasNext() {    return innerIterator.hasNext();  }  @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")  @Override  public E next() {    Bar bar = innerIterator.next();    return new E(bar);  }  @Override  public void remove() {    throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Don't remove from FooIterator!");  }  private Iterator<Bar> innerIterator;}...except, of course, this doesn't work because I can't instantiate a new E from a Bar.I would only ever use this with an E that has a constructor that takes a Bar. Is there any way to "prove" that to the compiler, or to just throw a runtime error if E doesn't have an appropriate constructor?Or perhaps I'm just not using the right design pattern here? I've been doing a lot of C++ recently, and I feel like I might be approaching this the wrong way.
Please using this api: Iterator.next.
Answer: Making assumptions about type parameters?: :You can use Java's Generics to enforce that E must have a constructor that takes a Bar. You can do this by creating a new method in your FooIterator class that takes an E and a Bar, and then call this method in your next() method. Here's an example:

```java
public class FooIterator<E> implements Iterator<E> {
  public FooIterator(Collection<Bar> bars) {
    innerIterator = bars.iterator();
  }

  @Override
  public boolean hasNext() {
    return innerIterator.hasNext();
  }

  @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
  @Override
  public E next() {
    Bar bar = innerIterator.next();
    return createNewInstance(bar);
  }

  private E createNewInstance(Bar bar) {
    try {
      return (E) Class.forName(E.class.getName()).getConstructor(Bar.class).newInstance(bar);
    } catch (Exception e) {
      throw new RuntimeException("Class " + E.class.getName() + " must have a constructor that takes a Bar", e);
    }
  }

  @Override
  public void remove() {
    throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Don't remove from FooIterator!");
  }

  private Iterator<Bar> innerIterator;
}
```

In this code, the createNewInstance() method uses reflection to create a new instance of E with a Bar constructor. If the constructor does not exist, or if it throws an exception, it throws a RuntimeException. This way, you can ensure that E must have a constructor that takes a Bar.

Please note that this solution is not type-safe. If E is not a subclass of Bar, this will not compile. If you want to ensure that E is a subclass of Bar, you would need to add some additional type checking.

Also, this solution is not recommended for production code. It's a bit of a hack and can lead to runtime errors if the class E does not have a constructor that takes a Bar. It's better to use a factory pattern or a builder pattern to create instances of E.

